    <div class="container">

      <div class="row page-header">
          <h1>First Collaborator Meeting 2013, São Paulo</h1>
      </div>

      <div class="row">
        <div class="span2"></div>
        <div class="span8 description">
		<P><BR></P>
		<P>During the week of
			March 4-8 collaborators of our Dimensions of Biodiversity grant held
			our fist organizational meeting at the headquarters of FAPESP
			(Fundação de Amparo à Pesquisa do Estado de São Paulo) in São
			Paulo, Brazil.  FAPESP, along with the US National Science Foundation
			(NSF), and the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA),
			is one of our funding partners.  Altogether the meeting involved 30
			collaborators from Brazil (6 institutions), the United States (8),
			Canada (1), Great Britain (1), and Argentina (1).  As the title of
			our grant proposal —<I>Assembly and evolution of the Amazon biota
			and its environment: an integrated approach—</I> implies, our goal
			is to integrate research across numerous disciplines in order to
			document a detailed picture of the evolution of the Amazonian biota
			and environment, particularly over Plio-Pleistocene times. 
		</P>
		<P><BR></P>
		<P>The first goal of the
			meeting was for the collaborators to become more acquainted with each
			other's research and how we might establish integrative activities. 
			Thus, on the first day we held a public symposium that filled the
			large auditorium at FAPESP, with most of the audience being students
			from São Paulo State but many other Brazilian states as well. 
			Nearly all collaborators spoke about their research within the
			context of the overall project, and in so doing gave the audience a
			great overview of the science challenges confronting Amazonian
			biodiversity and its environment.  
			The <a href="">program of the symposium</a> is available.
		</P>
		<P><BR></P>
		<P>The symposium paved the
			way for four days of discussions that had plenary sessions of all
			collaborators but mostly involved small discussions within and across
			disciplines.  Through these meetings, research activities were
			planned for the next one to two years.  
			</P>
		<P><BR></P>
		
		<P>
			Finally,
			we are grateful to FAPESP for making their facilities available to
			us, and special thanks are due to the FAPESP staff, who made our stay
			easy and enjoyable. 
		</P>
          
          
        </div>
      </div>



